              <h3>Temperature Inaccuracy</h3>
              <p>
                One of the most common issues with ovens is temperature
                inaccuracy, where the oven does not heat to the temperature set
                on the dial. This can be caused by a faulty thermostat, a
                malfunctioning temperature sensor, or worn-out heating elements.
                As a result, food may cook unevenly, take longer to prepare, or
                burn on the outside while remaining undercooked inside. Regular
                calibration and maintenance checks can help identify and resolve
                these issues. In some cases, replacing the thermostat or sensor
                may be necessary to restore accurate temperature control.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Uneven Cooking</h3>
              <p>
                Uneven cooking is another prevalent problem that can arise in
                ovens. This issue often results from poor air circulation within
                the oven cavity, which can be due to a malfunctioning convection
                fan, blocked vents, or improper rack placement. Additionally,
                old or worn-out heating elements may fail to distribute heat
                evenly. To troubleshoot, ensure that the convection fan is
                working correctly and that vents are not obstructed. Rotating
                and repositioning food during cooking can also help, but if the
                problem persists, professional inspection may be necessary to
                identify and repair the underlying cause.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Door Seal Problems</h3>
              <p>
                A faulty oven door seal can lead to heat escaping from the oven,
                causing inefficient cooking and increased energy consumption.
                The door gasket, typically made of rubber, can become worn,
                cracked, or loose over time, compromising the oven's ability to
                maintain a consistent internal temperature. This issue can also
                lead to longer preheating times and uneven cooking results. To
                address door seal problems, inspect the gasket regularly for
                signs of wear and tear, and replace it if necessary. Ensuring a
                tight seal when closing the oven door is crucial for optimal
                performance and energy efficiency.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Ignition Issues in Gas Ovens</h3>
